    <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
      <body>
        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="Aink427-kilavi">piriyum kol eṉṟu aiyuṟṟu uṭaṉpaṭāmai mēṟkoṇṭu oḻukukiṉṟa talaimakaṭkut tāṉ pirivu oḻintataṟkuk kāraṇam kūṟit tēṟṟiyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">To the heroine whose conduct was such that, thinking 'will [he] separate', had doubted [him] and taken on [a stance of] disagreement, he told the reason for having ceased his separation and clarified [this].<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">I have translated <foreign xml:lang="ta-Latn">tēṟṟu-tal</foreign> literally here as 'to make clear', as I believe that is the base meaning and that its extended connotation of reassurance does not necessitate translating differently. One 'clears up' a doubts in someone else mind, as is the case in this <foreign xml:lang="ta-Latn">kiḷavi</foreign>.</note></p>
            </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
          <lg xml:id="Aink427">        
            <l>pēramar malarkkaṇ maṭantai nīyē</l>
            <l>kāretir poḻuteṉa viṭalol lāyē</l>
            <l>pōruṭai vēntaṉ pācaṟai</l>
            <l>vārā ṉavaṉeṉac celavaḻuṅ kiṉaṉē.</l>
                       </lg>   
                       <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>O young woman with big beautiful eyes like blossoms,</l>
<l>you did not agree to [me] leaving [you]<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">The agent and object of the verbal noun <q xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">viṭal</hi></q> can be reversed. In that case, the heroine would not agree to let him go.</note></l>
  <l>as [it is] time for the rainy season.</l>
<l>The warring king has delayed the journey, thinking,</l>
<l>'He will not come to the war camp.'</l></lg>

        </div>
      </body>
    </text>
